root_causes: First validation statement (sel if not miss(B2cDKx5_99) and ~any(B2cDKx5_99,0,1)) will flag a value of 99 as invalid even though the second block is intended to allow 99 as an alternative encoding. The two checks conflict and cause false positives for 99.

instructions:
Make the acceptance criteria consistent. Either require binary coding only OR allow 99 as an alternative code — do not run a binary-only check first. For example, to accept 0/1 or 99, replace the first sel with:
sel if not miss(B2cDKx5_99) and ~any(B2cDKx5_99,0,1,99).
Alternatively remove the first (binary-only) block and keep only a single check that permits the expected encodings (e.g. 0/1 or 99).
If other special missing codes (97/98) are used in the dataset, include them explicitly in the allowed list or handle them consistently (e.g. any(B2cDKx5_99,0,1,97,98,99) if appropriate).
